Background & Context¶

There is a huge demand for used cars in the Indian market today. As sales of new cars have slowed down in the recent past, the pre-owned car market has continued to grow over the past few years and is now larger than the new car market. Cars4U is a budding tech start-up that aims to find footholds in this market.

In 2018-19, around 4 million second-hand cars were bought and sold, compared to 3.6 million new cars. There is a slowdown in new car sales, and that could mean that the demand is shifting to the pre-owned market. In fact, some car sellers replace their old cars with pre-owned cars instead of buying new ones. Unlike new cars, where price and supply are fairly deterministic and managed by OEMs (Original Equipment Manufacturer), used cars are very different, with huge uncertainty in both pricing and supply. Keeping this in mind, the pricing scheme of these used cars becomes important in order to grow in the market.

As a senior data scientist at Cars4U, I need to come up with a pricing model that can effectively predict the price of used cars and can help the business in devising profitable strategies using differential pricing.

Objectives¶

  • Explore and visualize the dataset.
  • Build a linear regression model to predict the prices of used cars.
  • Generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the business.

Data Dictionary¶

  • S.No.: Serial Number
  • Name: Name of the car which includes Brand name and Model name
  • Location: The location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase Cities
  • Year: Manufacturing year of the car
  • Kilometers_driven: The total kilometers driven in the car by the previous owner(s) in KM.
  • Fuel_Type: The type of fuel used by the car. (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)
  • Transmission: The type of transmission used by the car. (Automatic / Manual)
  • Owner: Type of ownership
  • Mileage: The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg
  • Engine: The displacement volume of the engine in CC.
  • Power: The maximum power of the engine in bhp.
  • Seats: The number of seats in the car.
  • New_Price: The price of a new car of the same model in INR Lakhs.(1 Lakh = 100, 000)
  • Price: The price of the used car in INR Lakhs

def strip_engine(Engine):
    """In the "Engine" column, I will replace "CC" with an
    empty string and convert to a float.  Non-strings are 
    np.nans and are kept as np.nan."""
    if isinstance(Engine, str):
        return float(Engine.replace(' CC', ''))
    else:
        return np.nan
    
def strip_newprice(New_Price):
    """In the "New_Price" column, I will replace 'Lakh' and
    'Cr' with an empty string and convert to a float.  Non-
    strings are np.nans and are kept as np.nan."""
    if isinstance(New_Price, str):
        if 'Lakh' in New_Price:
                return float(New_Price.replace(' Lakh', ''))
        else: 
                return float(New_Price.replace(' Cr', ''))
    else:
        return np.nan

    empty string and convert to a float.  Non-strings are 
    np.nans and are kept as np.nan."""
    if isinstance(Power, str):
       return float(Power.replace(' bhp', ''))
    else:
       return np.nan

#For 'Mileage', some have a value of 'o.o kmpl'.  Since it is not logical
#to have a mileage of 0, I will change these values to 'nan'
df['Mileage'].replace('0.0 kmpl', np.nan, inplace = True)
def strip_mileage(Mileage):
    """In the Mileage column, I will use a nested if to replace "kmpl"
    and "km/kg" with an empty string and convert to a float.  Non-strings 
    are np.nans and are kept as np.nan."""
    if isinstance(Mileage, str):
           if 'kmpl' in Mileage:
                return float(Mileage.replace(' kmpl', ''))
           else: 
                return float(Mileage.replace(' km/kg', ''))
    else:
       return np.nan

#collecting columns that need to be stripped, and looping over them
col_transforms = {
    'New_Price': strip_newprice,
    'Engine': strip_engine,
    'Power': strip_power,
    'Mileage': strip_mileage
    }

for k,v in col_transforms.items():
    df[k] = df[k].map(v)

#Confirming skewness visually with a histogram/box plot combo performed on all numeric variables
#I will define a function to create this plot
def hist_box(feature, figsize=(15,10), bins = None):
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(nrows = 2,
                                           sharex = True, # Share the same x-axis
                                           gridspec_kw = {"height_ratios": (.25, .75)}, 
                                           figsize = figsize 
                                           )
    sns.boxplot(feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color='red') # box plot with star on the mean
    sns.distplot(feature, kde=F, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins) if bins else sns.distplot(feature, kde=False, ax=ax_hist2)
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.mean(feature), color='g', linestyle='--')
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.median(feature), color='black', linestyle='-') # Add green mean and black median to histogram

New Price, as should probably be expected, has a strong correlation with price. However, given the fact that we are missing so many values, coupled with the fact that new car prices vary significantly, I don't think it would be appropriate to replace this variable with the mean, median, or any other measure of central tendency. If we simply drop all rows that are missing new price, I feel like we lose more than we gain. Therefore, I will drop this variable. Future research should include getting this data from sources like Kelley Blue Book, and including it in a future regression.

  • I will include a regression with new price, dropping all rows where it is missing, just to see what happens. This may make a good case for gathering this data to be used in the future

Observations¶

  • With the New_Price data included, even with significantly less data, I saw a slight improvement in explaining my training data
  • However, I saw a slight decrease in explaining my test data.
  • Conclusion: As expected, I can not justify using the "New_Price" variable. Even the increase in score for training data might only be explained by fluke correlations that are not actually meaningful. I could test this further by doing an adjusted R2 score; however, since the test data did not show an improvement, I will go ahead and reject the New Price column outright. I still feel like I have built a solid case for imputing this data in a future project, populated with data that is easily accessible from sources like Kelley Blue Book. We lost 86% of our data by dropping these rows - if we had these rows, with a new variable that is clearly correlated with "Price", it seems likely to represent a meaningful improvement in our regression.

from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error, r2_score
# defining function for MAPE
def mape(targets, predictions):
    return np.mean(np.abs((targets - predictions)) / targets) * 100


# defining common function for all metrics
def model_perf(model, inp, out):
    """
    model: model
    inp: independent variables
    out: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(inp).flatten()
    y_act = out.values.flatten()

    return pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "MAE": mean_absolute_error(y_act, y_pred),
            "MAPE": mape(y_act, y_pred),
            "RMSE": np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_act, y_pred)),
            "R^2": r2_score(y_act, y_pred),
        },
        index=[0],
    )

Linearity of variables¶

Methodology:¶
  • Make a plot of fitted values vs residuals, if they don't follow any pattern, they we say the model is linear, otherwise model is showing signs of non-linearity.
In [112]:
fitted = linearmodelfinal.fittedvalues
In [113]:
sns.set_style("whitegrid")
sns.residplot(fitted, residual, color="purple")
plt.xlabel("Fitted Values")
plt.ylabel("Residuals")
plt.title("Residual vs Fitted plot")
plt.show()

Observations¶

  • There MIGHT be a slight correlation at the left, but it clearly breaks down as the graph moves on
  • There is not enough of a correlation to conclude that the test is not satisfied
  • We can say that the model shows signs of linearity

Test for Normality¶

Methodology¶

  • Check for normality visually by doing a distribution plot of the residuals
  • Also can be checked using Shapiro-Wilk Test
In [114]:
sns.distplot(residual)
plt.title("Normality of residuals")
plt.show()

Observations:¶

  • Looks normal. Passes normality check!

Homoscedasticity¶

Methodology¶

  • Run goldfeldquant test
  • Null Hypothesis: Results are homoscedastic
  • Alternative Hypothesis: Results exhibit heteroscedasticity
In [115]:
import statsmodels.stats.api as sms
from statsmodels.compat import lzip

name = ["F statistic", "p-value"]
test = sms.het_goldfeldquandt(residual, Xfinal)
lzip(name, test)

[('F statistic', 0.9151116625825021), ('p-value', 0.9922627574120716)]

Observations:¶

  • Since p-value is WELL above 0.05, we can reject our alternative hypothesis. Residuals are homoscedastic
  • All assumptions of linear regression are satisfied!

Conclusions¶

  • Among numerical variables, year is the biggest indicator of price, which should be expected. For every additional year newer, the value of the used vehicle increases by 827,800 Lakhs.

  • Increased power increases the price, while increased mileage and kilometers driven decreases the price. I was not expecting an increase in mileage to coincide with a decrease in price.

  • Location matters. Some locations increase the price, the highest being Coimbatore, while some decrease the price, the lowest being Kolkata

  • Electric vehicles will definitely command the most price. If the fuel type is LPG, the price will increase, while other fuel types will decrease the price. The lowest priced cars are those powered by petrol

  • In general, with few exceptions, having more seats will result in a lower price.

  • There is little statistical evidence to suggest how price is affected by number of previous owners. One would expect the number of previous owners to be inversely proportional to the price, but more research is needed

  • New price would appear to be a strong indicator of current price; however, the data was missing from 86% of the columns, so this variable was dropped. In the future, this data could make a significant difference

  • Other factors, such as condition of the vehicle, should be considered in future projects.
